uents and communities, but also to frame that need as potentially dangerous. Using international case studies this book shows how vulnerability governance permeates policy sectors – transforming the methods used to govern, problematise and resolve – bringing questions of risk management and security into social policy, but simultaneously brings social policy sectors into counterterrorism delivery. The combination of welfare state and security logics brings interventions deeper into societies, securitising communities and individuals on account of their needs, governing the social through security politics.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aRiskxSocial aspects. 0aSocial policy. 0aTerrorismxPrevention. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  acountering violent extremism.  agovernance.  aliberalism.  amigration.  aprevention.  aradicalisation.  asecurity.  asocial policy.  avulnerability.  awelfare state.1 aAked, Hil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirol, Ali Fuat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aC. Fletcher, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuccu, Fabrizio Leonardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFey, Jana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGressgård, Randi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Barbara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeath-Kelly, Charlotte, econtributor.4